  "prompt": "Can I apply for an E-2 visa while my green card is on process?",
  "response": "Yes, you can apply for an E-2 visa while your green card application is in process, but there are important considerations to keep in mind:\n\n### 1. **Dual Intent**\n   - The **E-2 visa** is a non-immigrant visa and is not considered a \"dual intent\" visa, meaning it is typically issued for temporary purposes. However, the U.S. government does not explicitly prohibit E-2 visa holders from pursuing permanent residency (a green card) concurrently.\n   - If you apply for an E-2 visa while your green card application is pending, you must demonstrate that you intend to maintain temporary status in the U.S. and do not have the immediate intent to immigrate permanently.\n\n### 2. **Impact on Green Card Application**\n   - Applying for an E-2 visa does not directly affect your green card application. However, if your green card application is based on an adjustment of status (AOS) within the U.S., leaving the country could abandon your AOS unless you have obtained Advance Parole (a travel document).\n   - If your green card application is through consular processing (outside the U.S.), applying for an E-2 visa will not impact it.\n\n### 3. **Consular Processing vs. Adjustment of Status**\n   - If your green card application is being processed through **consular processing** (you are outside the U.S.), you can apply for an E-2 visa without issue.\n   - If your green card application is an **adjustment of status** (you are in the U.S.), applying for an E-2 visa could complicate matters, as leaving the U.S. without Advance Parole may result in the abandonment of your AOS.\n\n### 4. **Intent and Visa Issuance**\n   - When applying for the E-2 visa, you will need to convince the consular officer or immigration officer that you intend to maintain temporary status in the U.S., even though you have a pending green card application. This can be challenging, as the officer may view your green card application as evidence of immigrant intent.\n\n### 5. **Consult an Immigration Attorney**\n   - Given the complexity of these situations, it is highly recommended to consult with an experienced immigration attorney to assess your specific circumstances and avoid any unintended consequences.\n\nIn summary, while it is possible to apply for an E-2 visa while your green card is in process, doing so requires careful planning and consideration to avoid jeopardizing either application.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
